# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pagerank-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In graph theory and network analysis, indicators of **centrality** assign numbers or rankings to nodes within a graph corresponding to their network position.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Applications include identifying the most influential person(s) in a social network, key infrastructure nodes in the Internet or urban networks, super-spreaders of disease, and brain networks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Centrality concepts were first developed in social network analysis, and many of the terms used to measure centrality reflect their sociological origin.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Over time, the concept has expanded substantially, leading to the development of hundreds of distinct centrality measures, the most comprehensive listing of which is documented in the CentralityZoo online catalogue.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Centrality indices are answers to the question "What characterizes an important vertex?" The answer is given in terms of a real-valued function on the vertices of a graph, where the values produced are expected to provide a ranking which identifies the most important nodes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The word "importance" has a wide number of meanings, leading to many different definitions of centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Two categorization schemes have been proposed.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] "Importance" can be conceived in relation to a type of flow or transfer across the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This allows centralities to be classified by the type of flow they consider important.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] "Importance" can alternatively be conceived as involvement in the cohesiveness of the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This allows centralities to be classified based on how they measure cohesiveness.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Both of these approaches divide centralities in distinct categories.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] A further conclusion is that a centrality which is appropriate for one category will often "get it wrong" when applied to a different category.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Many, though not all, centrality measures effectively count the number of paths (also called walks) of some type going through a given vertex; the measures differ in how the relevant walks are defined and counted.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Restricting consideration to this group allows for taxonomy which places many centralities on a spectrum from those concerned with walks of length one (degree centrality) to infinite walks (eigenvector centrality).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Other centrality measures, such as betweenness centrality focus not just on overall connectedness but occupying positions that are pivotal to the network's connectivity.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] A network can be considered a description of the paths along which something flows.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This allows a characterization based on the type of flow and the type of path encoded by the centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] A flow can be based on transfers, where each indivisible item goes from one node to another, like a package delivery going from the delivery site to the client's house.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] A second case is serial duplication, in which an item is replicated so that both the source and the target have it.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] An example is the propagation of information through gossip, with the information being propagated in a private way and with both the source and the target nodes being informed at the end of the process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The last case is parallel duplication, with the item being duplicated to several links at the same time, like a radio broadcast which provides the same information to many listeners at once.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Likewise, the type of path can be constrained to geodesics (shortest paths), paths (no vertex is visited more than once), trails (vertices can be visited multiple times, no edge is traversed more than once), or walks (vertices and edges can be visited/traversed multiple times).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] An alternative classification can be derived from how the centrality is constructed.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Centralities are either *radial* or *medial.* Radial centralities count walks which start/end from the given vertex.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The degree and eigenvalue centralities are examples of radial centralities, counting the number of walks of length one or length infinity.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Medial centralities count walks which pass through the given vertex.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The canonical example is Freeman's betweenness centrality, the number of shortest paths which pass through the given vertex.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Likewise, the counting can capture either the *volume* or the *length* of walks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Volume is the total number of walks of the given type.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The three examples from the previous paragraph fall into this category.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Length captures the distance from the given vertex to the remaining vertices in the graph.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Closeness centrality, the total geodesic distance from a given vertex to all other vertices, is the best known example.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Note that this classification is independent of the type of walk counted (i.e. walk, trail, path, geodesic).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Borgatti and Everett propose that this typology provides insight into how best to compare centrality measures.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Centralities placed in the same box in this 2×2 classification are similar enough to make plausible alternatives; one can reasonably compare which is better for a given application.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Measures from different boxes, however, are categorically distinct.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Any evaluation of relative fitness can only occur within the context of predetermining which category is more applicable, rendering the comparison moot.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The characterization by walk structure shows that almost all centralities in wide use are radial-volume measures.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] These encode the belief that a vertex's centrality is a function of the centrality of the vertices it is associated with.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Centralities distinguish themselves on how association is defined.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Bonacich showed that if association is defined in terms of walks, then a family of centralities can be defined based on the length of walk considered.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Degree centrality counts walks of length one, while eigenvalue centrality counts walks of length infinity.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Alternative definitions of association are also reasonable.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Alpha centrality allows vertices to have an external source of influence.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Estrada's subgraph centrality proposes only counting closed paths (triangles, squares, etc.).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The heart of such measures is the observation that powers of the graph's adjacency matrix gives the number of walks of length given by that power.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Similarly, the matrix exponential is also closely related to the number of walks of a given length.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] An initial transformation of the adjacency matrix allows a different definition of the type of walk counted.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Bonacich's family of measures does not transform the adjacency matrix.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Alpha centrality replaces the adjacency matrix with its resolvent.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Subgraph centrality replaces the adjacency matrix with its trace.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] A startling conclusion is that regardless of the initial transformation of the adjacency matrix, all such approaches have common limiting behavior.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] As $\beta$ approaches zero, the indices converge to degree centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] As $\beta$ approaches its maximal value, the indices converge to eigenvalue centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The common feature of most of the aforementioned standard measures is that they assess the importance of a node by focusing only on the role that a node plays by itself.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] However, in many applications such an approach is inadequate because of synergies that may occur if the functioning of nodes is considered in groups.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] For example, consider the problem of stopping an epidemic.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Looking at above image of network, which nodes should we vaccinate?
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Based on previously described measures, we want to recognize nodes that are the most important in disease spreading.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Approaches based only on centralities, that focus on individual features of nodes, may not be a good idea.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Nodes in the red square, individually cannot stop disease spreading, but considering them as a group, we clearly see that they can stop disease if it has started in nodes $v_{1}$ , $v_{4}$ , and $v_{5}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Game-theoretic centralities try to consult described problems and opportunities, using tools from game-theory.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The approach proposed in uses the Shapley value.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Because of the time-complexity hardness of the Shapley value calculation, most efforts in this domain are driven into implementing new algorithms and methods which rely on a peculiar topology of the network or a special character of the problem.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Such an approach may lead to reducing time-complexity from exponential to polynomial.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Similarly, the solution concept authority distribution () applies the Shapley-Shubik power index, rather than the Shapley value, to measure the bilateral direct influence between the players.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The distribution is indeed a type of eigenvector centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] It is used to sort big data objects in Hu (2020), such as ranking U.S. colleges.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Centrality indices have two important limitations, one obvious and the other subtle.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The obvious limitation is that a centrality which is optimal for one application is often sub-optimal for a different application.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Indeed, if this were not so, we would not need so many different centralities.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] An illustration of this phenomenon is provided by the Krackhardt kite graph, for which three different notions of centrality give three different choices of the most central vertex.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The more subtle limitation is the commonly held fallacy that vertex centrality indicates the relative importance of vertices.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Centrality indices are explicitly designed to produce a ranking which allows indication of the most important vertices.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This they do well, under the limitation just noted.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] They are not designed to measure the influence of nodes in general.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Recently, network physicists have begun developing node influence metrics to address this problem.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Firstly, a ranking only orders vertices by importance, it does not quantify the difference in importance between different levels of the ranking.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This may be mitigated by applying Freeman centralization to the centrality measure in question, which provide some insight to the importance of nodes depending on the differences of their centralization scores.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Furthermore, Freeman centralization enables one to compare several networks by comparing their highest centralization scores.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Secondly, the features which (correctly) identify the most important vertices in a given network/application do not necessarily generalize to the remaining vertices.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] For the majority of other network nodes the rankings may be meaningless.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This explains why, for example, only the first few results of a Google image search appear in a reasonable order.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The pagerank is a highly unstable measure, showing frequent rank reversals after small adjustments of the jump parameter.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] While the failure of centrality indices to generalize to the rest of the network may at first seem counter-intuitive, it follows directly from the above definitions.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Complex networks have heterogeneous topology.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] To the extent that the optimal measure depends on the network structure of the most important vertices, a measure which is optimal for such vertices is sub-optimal for the remainder of the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Historically first and conceptually simplest is **degree centrality**, which is defined as the number of links incident upon a node (i.e., the number of ties that a node has).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The degree can be interpreted in terms of the immediate risk of a node for catching whatever is flowing through the network (such as a virus, or some information).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In the case of a directed network (where ties have direction), we usually define two separate measures of degree centrality, namely indegree and outdegree.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Accordingly, indegree is a count of the number of ties directed to the node and outdegree is the number of ties that the node directs to others.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] When ties are associated to some positive aspects such as friendship or collaboration, indegree is often interpreted as a form of popularity, and outdegree as gregariousness.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Calculating degree centrality for all the nodes in a graph takes $\Theta (V^{2})$ in a dense adjacency matrix representation of the graph, and for edges takes $\Theta (E)$ in a sparse matrix representation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The definition of centrality on the node level can be extended to the whole graph, in which case we are speaking of *graph centralization*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Let $v*$ be the node with highest degree centrality in G .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] where TMH increases by appearance of degree centrality in the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In a connected graph, the normalized **closeness centrality** (or **closeness**) of a node is the average length of the shortest path between the node and all other nodes in the graph.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Thus the more central a node is, the closer it is to all other nodes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Closeness was defined by Alex Bavelas (1950) as the reciprocal of the **farness**, that is ${\textstyle C_{B}(v)=(\sum _{u}d(u,v))^{-1}}$ where $d(u,v)$ is the distance between vertices *u* and *v*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This normalisation allows comparisons between nodes of graphs of different sizes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] For many graphs, there is a strong correlation between the inverse of closeness and the logarithm of degree, $(C(v))^{-1}\approx -\alpha \ln(k_{v})+\beta$ where $k_{v}$ is the degree of vertex *v* while α and β are constants for each network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Taking distances *from* or *to* all other nodes is irrelevant in undirected graphs, whereas it can produce totally different results in directed graphs (e.g. a website can have a high closeness centrality from an outgoing link, but low closeness centrality from incoming links).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] where $1/d(u,v)=0$ if there is no path from *u* to *v*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Harmonic centrality can be normalized by dividing by $N-1$ , where N is the number of nodes in the graph.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Harmonic centrality was proposed by Marchiori and Latora (2000) and then independently by Dekker (2005), using the name "valued centrality," and by Rochat (2009).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] For each pair of vertices (*s*,*t*), determine the fraction of shortest paths that pass through the vertex in question (here, vertex *v*).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Sum this fraction over all pairs of vertices (*s*,*t*).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] where $\sigma _{st}$ is total number of shortest paths from node s to node t and $\sigma _{st}(v)$ is the number of those paths that pass through v .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The betweenness may be normalised by dividing through the number of pairs of vertices not including *v*, which for directed graphs is $(n-1)(n-2)$ and for undirected graphs is $(n-1)(n-2)/2$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] For example, in an undirected star graph, the center vertex (which is contained in every possible shortest path) would have a betweenness of $(n-1)(n-2)/2$ (1, if normalised) while the leaves (which are contained in no shortest paths) would have a betweenness of 0.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] From a calculation aspect, both betweenness and closeness centralities of all vertices in a graph involve calculating the shortest paths between all pairs of vertices on a graph, which requires $O(V^{3})$ time with the Floyd–Warshall algorithm.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] However, on sparse graphs, Johnson's algorithm may be more efficient, taking $O(|V||E|+|V|^{2}\log |V|)$ time.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In the case of unweighted graphs the calculations can be done with Brandes' algorithm which takes $O(|V||E|)$ time.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Normally, these algorithms assume that graphs are undirected and connected with the allowance of loops and multiple edges.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] When specifically dealing with network graphs, often graphs are without loops or multiple edges to maintain simple relationships (where edges represent connections between two people or vertices).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In this case, using Brandes' algorithm will divide final centrality scores by 2 to account for each shortest path being counted twice.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] For a given graph $G:=(V,E)$ with $|V|$ number of vertices let $A=(a_{v,t})$ be the adjacency matrix, i.e. $a_{v,t}=1$ if vertex v is linked to vertex t , and $a_{v,t}=0$ otherwise.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] where $M(v)$ is a set of the neighbors of v and $\lambda$ is a constant.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In general, there will be many different eigenvalues $\lambda$ for which a non-zero eigenvector solution exists.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Since the entries in the adjacency matrix are non-negative, there is a unique largest eigenvalue, which is real and positive, by the Perron–Frobenius theorem.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This greatest eigenvalue results in the desired centrality measure.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The $v^{th}$ component of the related eigenvector then gives the relative centrality score of the vertex v in the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The eigenvector is only defined up to a common factor, so only the ratios of the centralities of the vertices are well defined.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] To define an absolute score one must normalise the eigenvector, e.g., such that the sum over all vertices is 1 or the total number of vertices *n*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Power iteration is one of many eigenvalue algorithms that may be used to find this dominant eigenvector.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Furthermore, this can be generalized so that the entries in *A* can be real numbers representing connection strengths, as in a stochastic matrix.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] where $\alpha$ is an attenuation factor in $(0,1)$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Katz centrality can be viewed as a variant of eigenvector centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] It is shown that the principal eigenvector (associated with the largest eigenvalue of A , the adjacency matrix) is the limit of Katz centrality as $\alpha$ approaches ${\tfrac {1}{\lambda }}$ from below.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] is the number of neighbors of node j (or number of outbound links in a directed graph).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Compared to eigenvector centrality and Katz centrality, one major difference is the scaling factor $L(j)$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Another difference between PageRank and eigenvector centrality is that the PageRank vector is a left hand eigenvector (note the factor $a_{ji}$ has indices reversed).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] A slew of centrality measures exist to determine the 'importance' of a single node in a complex network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] However, these measures quantify the importance of a node in purely topological terms, and the value of the node does not depend on the 'state' of the node in any way.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] It remains constant regardless of network dynamics.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This is true even for the weighted betweenness measures.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] However, a node may very well be centrally located in terms of betweenness centrality or another centrality measure, but may not be 'centrally' located in the context of a network in which there is percolation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Percolation of a 'contagion' occurs in complex networks in a number of scenarios.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] For example, viral or bacterial infection can spread over social networks of people, known as contact networks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The spread of disease can also be considered at a higher level of abstraction, by contemplating a network of towns or population centres, connected by road, rail or air links.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Computer viruses can spread over computer networks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Rumours or news about business offers and deals can also spread via social networks of people.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In all of these scenarios, a 'contagion' spreads over the links of a complex network, altering the 'states' of the nodes as it spreads, either recoverable or otherwise.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] For example, in an epidemiological scenario, individuals go from 'susceptible' to 'infected' state as the infection spreads.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The states the individual nodes can take in the above examples could be binary (such as received/not received a piece of news), discrete (susceptible/infected/recovered), or even continuous (such as the proportion of infected people in a town), as the contagion spreads.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The common feature in all these scenarios is that the spread of contagion results in the change of node states in networks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Percolation centrality (PC) was proposed with this in mind, which specifically measures the importance of nodes in terms of aiding the percolation through the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] This measure was proposed by Piraveenan et al.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] where $\sigma _{sr}$ is the total number of shortest paths from node s to node r and $\sigma _{sr}(v)$ is the number of those paths that pass through v .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The percolation state of the node i at time t is denoted by ${x^{t}}_{i}$ and two special cases are when ${x^{t}}_{i}=0$ which indicates a non-percolated state at time t whereas when ${x^{t}}_{i}=1$ which indicates a fully percolated state at time t .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The values in between indicate partially percolated states ( e.g., in a network of townships, this would be the percentage of people infected in that town).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The attached weights to the percolation paths depend on the percolation levels assigned to the source nodes, based on the premise that the higher the percolation level of a source node is, the more important are the paths that originate from that node.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Nodes which lie on shortest paths originating from highly percolated nodes are therefore potentially more important to the percolation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The definition of PC may also be extended to include target node weights as well.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Percolation centrality calculations run in $O(NM)$ time with an efficient implementation adopted from Brandes' fast algorithm and if the calculation needs to consider target nodes weights, the worst case time is $O(N^{3})$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] The **centralization** of any network is a measure of how central its most central node is in relation to how central all the other nodes are.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Centralization measures then (a) calculate the sum in differences in centrality between the most central node in a network and all other nodes; and (b) divide this quantity by the theoretically largest such sum of differences in any network of the same size.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Thus, every centrality measure can have its own centralization measure.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In order to obtain better results in the ranking of the nodes of a given network, Alvarez-Socorro et. al. used dissimilarity measures (specific to the theory of classification and data mining) to enrich the centrality measures in complex networks.
