[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Transportation networks such as road networks and railway networks are studied extensively in transportation science and urban planning.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] A number of recent studies have focused on using centrality measures to analyze transportation networks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] While many of these studies simply use generic centrality measures such as Betweenness Centrality, custom centrality measures have also been defined specifically for transportation network analysis.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Prominent among them is **Transportation Centrality**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Transportation centrality measures the summation of the proportions of paths from pairs of nodes in a network which go through the node under consideration.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] In this respect it is similar to Betweenness Centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] However, unlike Betweenness Centrality which considers only shortest paths, Transportation Centrality considers all possible paths between a pair of nodes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/centrality] Therefore, Transportation Centrality is a generic version of Betweenness Centrality, and under certain conditions, it indeed reduces to Betweenness Centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] In graph theory, **eigenvector centrality** (also called **eigencentrality** or **prestige score**) is a measure of the influence of a node in a connected network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] Relative scores are assigned to all nodes in the network based on the concept that connections to high-scoring nodes contribute more to the score of the node in question than equal connections to low-scoring nodes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] A high eigenvector score means that a node is connected to many nodes who themselves have high scores.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] Google's PageRank and the Katz centrality are variants of the eigenvector centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] For a given graph $G:=(V,E)$ with $|V|$ vertices let $A=(a_{v,t})$ be the adjacency matrix, i.e. $a_{v,t}=1$ if vertex v is linked to vertex t , and $a_{v,t}=0$ otherwise.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] where $M(v)$ is the set of neighbors of v and $\lambda$ is a constant.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] However, the connectedness assumption and the additional requirement that all the entries in the eigenvector be non-negative imply (by the Perron–Frobenius theorem) that only the greatest eigenvalue results in the desired centrality measure.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] The $v^{\text{th}}$ component of the related eigenvector then gives the relative centrality score of the vertex v in the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] To define an absolute score, one must normalise the eigenvector e.g. such that the sum over all vertices is 1 or the total number of vertices *n*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] Google's PageRank is based on the normalized eigenvector centrality, or normalized prestige, combined with a random jump assumption.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] The PageRank of a node v has recursive dependence on the PageRank of other nodes that point to it.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] where $\mathbf {e}$ is the vector of ones, and $\mathbf {diag} (\mathbf {x} )$ is the diagonal matrix of vector $\mathbf {x}$ . $\mathbf {N}$ is a row-stochastic matrix.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] Eigenvector centrality is a measure of the influence a node has on a network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] If a node is pointed to by many nodes (which also have high eigenvector centrality) then that node will have high eigenvector centrality.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/eigenvector-centrality] The earliest use of eigenvector centrality is by Edmund Landau in an 1895 paper on scoring chess tournaments.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] In network theory, **link analysis** is a data-analysis technique used to evaluate relationships between nodes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Relationships may be identified among various types of nodes, including organizations, people and transactions.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Link analysis has been used for investigation of criminal activity (fraud, counterterrorism, and intelligence), computer security analysis, search engine optimization, market research, medical research, and art.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Knowledge discovery is an iterative and interactive process used to identify, analyze and visualize patterns in data.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Network analysis, link analysis and social network analysis are all methods of knowledge discovery, each a corresponding subset of the prior method.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Data gathering and processing requires access to data and has several inherent issues, including information overload and data errors.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Once data is collected, it will need to be transformed into a format that can be effectively used by both human and computer analyzers.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Manual or computer-generated visualizations tools may be mapped from the data, including network charts.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Several algorithms exist to help with analysis of data – Dijkstra's algorithm, breadth-first search, and depth-first search.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Link analysis focuses on analysis of relationships among nodes through visualization methods (network charts, association matrix).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Discover new patterns of interest (social network analysis, data mining).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Klerks categorized link analysis tools into 3 generations.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] The first generation was introduced in 1975 as the Anacpapa Chart of Harper and Harris.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] This method requires that a domain expert review data files, identify associations by constructing an association matrix, create a link chart for visualization and finally analyze the network chart to identify patterns of interest.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] This method requires extensive domain knowledge and is extremely time-consuming when reviewing vast amounts of data.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] In addition to the association matrix, the activities matrix can be used to produce actionable information, which has practical value and use to law-enforcement.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] The activities matrix, as the term might imply, centers on the actions and activities of people with respect to locations.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Whereas the association matrix focuses on the relationships between people, organizations, and/or properties.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] The distinction between these two types of matrices, while minor, is nonetheless significant in terms of the output of the analysis completed or rendered.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Second generation tools consist of automatic graphics-based analysis tools such as IBM i2 Analyst's Notebook, Netmap, ClueMaker and Watson.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] These tools offer the ability to automate the construction and updates of the link chart once an association matrix is manually created, however, analysis of the resulting charts and graphs still requires an expert with extensive domain knowledge.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] The third generation of link-analysis tools like DataWalk allow the automatic visualization of linkages between elements in a data set, that can then serve as the canvas for further exploration or manual updates.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] With the vast amounts of data and information that are stored electronically, users are confronted with multiple unrelated sources of information available for analysis.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Data analysis techniques are required to make effective and efficient use of the data.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Bolton & Hand define statistical data analysis as either supervised or unsupervised methods.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Supervised learning methods require that rules are defined within the system to establish what is expected or unexpected behavior.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Unsupervised learning methods review data in comparison to the norm and detect statistical outliers.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Supervised learning methods are limited in the scenarios that can be handled as this method requires that training rules are established based on previous patterns.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Unsupervised learning methods can provide detection of broader issues, however, may result in a higher false-positive ratio if the behavioral norm is not well established or understood.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Data itself has inherent issues including integrity (or lack of) and continuous changes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Data may contain "errors of omission and commission because of faulty collection or handling, and when entities are actively attempting to deceive and/or conceal their actions".
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Sparrow highlights incompleteness (inevitability of missing data or links), fuzzy boundaries (subjectivity in deciding what to include) and dynamic changes (recognition that data is ever-changing) as the three primary problems with data analysis.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Once data is transformed into a usable format, open texture and cross referencing issues may arise.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Open texture was defined by Waismann as the unavoidable uncertainty in meaning when empirical terms are used in different contexts.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Uncertainty in meaning of terms presents problems when attempting to search and cross reference data from multiple sources.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] The primary method for resolving data analysis issues is reliance on domain knowledge from an expert.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] This is a very time-consuming and costly method of conducting link analysis and has inherent problems of its own.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] McGrath et al. conclude that the layout and presentation of a network diagram have a significant impact on the user's "perceptions of the existence of groups in networks".
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Even using domain experts may result in differing conclusions as analysis may be subjective.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Link analysis techniques have primarily been used for prosecution, as it is far easier to review historical data for patterns than it is to attempt to predict future actions.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Krebs demonstrated the use of an association matrix and link chart of the terrorist network associated with the 19 hijackers responsible for the September 11th attacks by mapping publicly available details made available following the attacks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Even with the advantages of hindsight and publicly available information on people, places and transactions, it is clear that there is missing data.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Alternatively, Picarelli argued that use of link analysis techniques could have been used to identify and potentially prevent illicit activities within the Aum Shinrikyo network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] "We must be careful of 'guilt by association'.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Heuristic-based tools utilize decision rules that are distilled from expert knowledge using structured data.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Template-based tools employ Natural Language Processing (NLP) to extract details from unstructured data that are matched to pre-defined templates.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Similarity-based approaches use weighted scoring to compare attributes and identify potential links.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Statistical approaches identify potential links based on lexical statistics.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/link-analysis] Chen propose a framework for automated network analysis and visualization called CrimeNet Explorer.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In probability theory and statistics, a **Markov chain** or **Markov process** is a stochastic process describing a sequence of possible events in which the probability of each event depends only on the state attained in the previous event.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Informally, this may be thought of as, "What happens next depends only on the state of affairs *now*." A countably infinite sequence, in which the chain moves state at discrete time steps, gives a discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time process is called a continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes are named in honor of the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Markov chains have many applications as statistical models of real-world processes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The adjectives *Markovian* and *Markov* are used to describe something that is related to a Markov process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A Markov process is a stochastic process that satisfies the Markov property (sometimes characterized as "memorylessness").
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In simpler terms, it is a process for which predictions can be made regarding future outcomes based solely on its present state and—most importantly—such predictions are just as good as the ones that could be made knowing the process's full history.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In other words, conditional on the present state of the system, its future and past states are independent.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is a type of Markov process that has either a discrete state space or a discrete index set (often representing time), but the precise definition of a Markov chain varies.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The system's state space and time parameter index need to be specified.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Note that there is no definitive agreement in the literature on the use of some of the terms that signify special cases of Markov processes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Usually the term "Markov chain" is reserved for a process with a discrete set of times, that is, a **discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC)**, but a few authors use the term "Markov process" to refer to a **continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC)** without explicit mention.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In addition, there are other extensions of Markov processes that are referred to as such but do not necessarily fall within any of these four categories (see Markov model).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Moreover, the time index need not necessarily be real-valued; like with the state space, there are conceivable processes that move through index sets with other mathematical constructs.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Notice that the general state space continuous-time Markov chain is general to such a degree that it has no designated term.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] While the time parameter is usually discrete, the state space of a Markov chain does not have any generally agreed-on restrictions: the term may refer to a process on an arbitrary state space.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] However, many applications of Markov chains employ finite or countably infinite state spaces, which have a more straightforward statistical analysis.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Besides time-index and state-space parameters, there are many other variations, extensions and generalizations (see Variations).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] For simplicity, most of this article concentrates on the discrete-time, discrete state-space case, unless mentioned otherwise.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The changes of state of the system are called transitions.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The probabilities associated with various state changes are called transition probabilities.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The process is characterized by a state space, a transition matrix describing the probabilities of particular transitions, and an initial state (or initial distribution) across the state space.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] By convention, we assume all possible states and transitions have been included in the definition of the process, so there is always a next state, and the process does not terminate.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A discrete-time random process involves a system which is in a certain state at each step, with the state changing randomly between steps.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The steps are often thought of as moments in time, but they can equally well refer to physical distance or any other discrete measurement.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Formally, the steps are the integers or natural numbers, and the random process is a mapping of these to states.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The Markov property states that the conditional probability distribution for the system at the next step (and in fact at all future steps) depends only on the current state of the system, and not additionally on the state of the system at previous steps.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Since the system changes randomly, it is generally impossible to predict with certainty the state of a Markov chain at a given point in the future.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] However, the statistical properties of the system's future can be predicted.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In many applications, it is these statistical properties that are important.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Markov studied Markov processes in the early 20th century, publishing his first paper on the topic in 1906.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes in continuous time were discovered long before his work in the early 20th century in the form of the Poisson process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Markov was interested in studying an extension of independent random sequences, motivated by a disagreement with Pavel Nekrasov who claimed independence was necessary for the weak law of large numbers to hold.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Markov later used Markov chains to study the distribution of vowels in Eugene Onegin, written by Alexander Pushkin, and proved a central limit theorem for such chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In 1912 Henri Poincaré studied Markov chains on finite groups with an aim to study card shuffling.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Other early uses of Markov chains include a diffusion model, introduced by Paul and Tatyana Ehrenfest in 1907, and a branching process, introduced by Francis Galton and Henry William Watson in 1873, preceding the work of Markov.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] After the work of Galton and Watson, it was later revealed that their branching process had been independently discovered and studied around three decades earlier by Irénée-Jules Bienaymé.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Starting in 1928, Maurice Fréchet became interested in Markov chains, eventually resulting in him publishing in 1938 a detailed study on Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Kolmogorov developed in a 1931 paper a large part of the early theory of continuous-time Markov processes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov was partly inspired by Louis Bachelier's 1900 work on fluctuations in the stock market as well as Norbert Wiener's work on Einstein's model of Brownian movement.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] He introduced and studied a particular set of Markov processes known as diffusion processes, where he derived a set of differential equations describing the processes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Independent of Kolmogorov's work, Sydney Chapman derived in a 1928 paper an equation, now called the Chapman–Kolmogorov equation, in a less mathematically rigorous way than Kolmogorov, while studying Brownian movement.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The differential equations are now called the Kolmogorov equations or the Kolmogorov–Chapman equations.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Other mathematicians who contributed significantly to the foundations of Markov processes include William Feller, starting in 1930s, and then later Eugene Dynkin, starting in the 1950s.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that there is a coin purse containing five coins worth 25¢ (quarters), five coins worth 10¢ (dimes) and five coins worth 5¢ (nickels).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] One by one, coins are randomly drawn from the purse and are set on a table.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If $X_{n}$ represents the total value of the coins set on the table after n draws, with $X_{0}=0$ , then the sequence $\{X_{n}:n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ is *not* a Markov process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] To see why this is the case, suppose that in the first six draws, all five nickels and a quarter are drawn.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If we know not just $X_{6}$ , but the earlier values as well, then we can determine which coins have been drawn, and we know that the next coin will not be a nickel; so we can determine that $X_{7}\geq \$0.60$ with probability 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] But if we do not know the earlier values, then based only on the value $X_{6}$ we might guess that we had drawn four dimes and two nickels, in which case it would certainly be possible to draw another nickel next.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Thus, our guesses about $X_{7}$ are impacted by our knowledge of values prior to $X_{6}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] However, it is possible to model this scenario as a Markov process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Instead of defining $X_{n}$ to represent the *total value* of the coins on the table, we could define $X_{n}$ to represent the *count* of the various coin types on the table.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] For instance, $X_{6}=1,0,5$ could be defined to represent the state where there is one quarter, zero dimes, and five nickels on the table after 6 one-by-one draws.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] This new model could be represented by $6\times 6\times 6=216$ possible states, where each state represents the number of coins of each type (from 0 to 5) that are on the table.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that the first draw results in state $X_{1}=0,1,0$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The probability of achieving $X_{2}$ now depends on $X_{1}$ ; for example, the state $X_{2}=1,0,1$ is not possible.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] After the second draw, the third draw depends on which coins have so far been drawn, but no longer only on the coins that were drawn for the first state (since probabilistically important information has since been added to the scenario).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In this way, the likelihood of the $X_{n}=i,j,k$ state depends exclusively on the outcome of the $X_{n-1}=\ell ,m,p$ state.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The possible values of *X**i* form a countable set *S* called the state space of the chain.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Since each row of **P** sums to one and all elements are non-negative, **P** is a right stochastic matrix.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] is a normalized ( ${\textstyle \sum _{i}\pi _{i}=1}$ ) multiple of a left eigenvector **e** of the transition matrix **P** with an eigenvalue of 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If there is more than one unit eigenvector then a weighted sum of the corresponding stationary states is also a stationary state.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] But for a Markov chain one is usually more interested in a stationary state that is the limit of the sequence of distributions for some initial distribution.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The values of a stationary distribution $\textstyle \pi _{i}$ are associated with the state space of **P** and its eigenvectors have their relative proportions preserved.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Since the components of π are positive and the constraint that their sum is unity can be rewritten as ${\textstyle \sum _{i}1\cdot \pi _{i}=1}$ we see that the dot product of π with a vector whose components are all 1 is unity and that π lies on a simplex.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is time-homogeneous, then the transition matrix **P** is the same after each step, so the *k*-step transition probability can be computed as the *k*-th power of the transition matrix, **P***k*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is irreducible and aperiodic, then there is a unique stationary distribution π.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] where **1** is the column vector with all entries equal to 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] This is stated by the Perron–Frobenius theorem.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If, by whatever means, ${\textstyle \lim _{k\to \infty }\mathbf {P} ^{k}}$ is found, then the stationary distribution of the Markov chain in question can be easily determined for any starting distribution, as will be explained below.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Because there are a number of different special cases to consider, the process of finding this limit if it exists can be a lengthy task.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] However, there are many techniques that can assist in finding this limit.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] where **I***n* is the identity matrix of size *n*, and **0***n*,*n* is the zero matrix of size *n*×*n*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Multiplying together stochastic matrices always yields another stochastic matrix, so **Q** must be a stochastic matrix (see the definition above).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] It is sometimes sufficient to use the matrix equation above and the fact that **Q** is a stochastic matrix to solve for **Q**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Here is one method for doing so: first, define the function *f*(**A**) to return the matrix **A** with its right-most column replaced with all 1's.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] One thing to notice is that if **P** has an element **P***i*,*i* on its main diagonal that is equal to 1 and the *i*th row or column is otherwise filled with 0's, then that row or column will remain unchanged in all of the subsequent powers **P***k*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Hence, the *i*th row or column of **Q** will have the 1 and the 0's in the same positions as in **P**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] As stated earlier, from the equation ${\boldsymbol {\pi }}={\boldsymbol {\pi }}\mathbf {P} ,$ (if exists) the stationary (or steady state) distribution **π** is a left eigenvector of row stochastic matrix **P**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Then assuming that **P** is diagonalizable or equivalently that **P** has *n* linearly independent eigenvectors, speed of convergence is elaborated as follows.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Let **U** be the matrix of eigenvectors (each normalized to having an L2 norm equal to 1) where each column is a left eigenvector of **P** and let **Σ** be the diagonal matrix of left eigenvalues of **P**, that is, **Σ** = diag(*λ*1,*λ*2,*λ*3,...,*λ**n*).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Since **P** is a row stochastic matrix, its largest left eigenvalue is 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If there is a unique stationary distribution, then the largest eigenvalue and the corresponding eigenvector is unique too (because there is no other **π** which solves the stationary distribution equation above).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Let **u***i* be the *i*-th column of **U** matrix, that is, **u***i* is the left eigenvector of **P** corresponding to λ*i*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If we multiply **x** with **P** from right and continue this operation with the results, in the end we get the stationary distribution **π**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Since **π** is parallel to **u**1(normalized by L2 norm) and **π**(*k*) is a probability vector, **π**(*k*) approaches to **a**1 **u**1 = **π** as *k* → ∞ with a speed in the order of *λ*2/*λ*1 exponentially.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] This follows because $|\lambda _{2}|\geq \cdots \geq |\lambda _{n}|,$ hence *λ*2/*λ*1 is the dominant term.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The smaller the ratio is, the faster the convergence is.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Random noise in the state distribution **π** can also speed up this convergence to the stationary distribution.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov chain $(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is defined by a finite or countable state space *S*, a transition rate matrix *Q* with dimensions equal to that of the state space and initial probability distribution defined on the state space.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] For *i* ≠ *j*, the elements *q**ij* are non-negative and describe the rate of the process transitions from state *i* to state *j*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The elements *q**ii* are chosen such that each row of the transition rate matrix sums to zero, while the row-sums of a probability transition matrix in a (discrete) Markov chain are all equal to one.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] There are three equivalent definitions of the process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Let $X_{t}$ be the random variable describing the state of the process at time *t*, and assume the process is in a state *i* at time *t*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Then, knowing $X_{t}=i$ , $X_{t+h}=j$ is independent of previous values $\left(X_{s}:s<t\right)$ , and as *h* → 0 for all *j* and for all *t*, $\Pr(X(t+h)=j\mid X(t)=i)=\delta _{ij}+q_{ij}h+o(h),$ where $\delta _{ij}$ is the Kronecker delta, using the little-o notation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The $q_{ij}$ can be seen as measuring how quickly the transition from *i* to *j* happens.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Define a discrete-time Markov chain *Y**n* to describe the *n*th jump of the process and variables *S*1, *S*2, *S*3, ... to describe holding times in each of the states where *S**i* follows the exponential distribution with rate parameter −*q**Y**i**Y**i*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] with initial condition P(0) is the identity matrix.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] "Locally interacting Markov chains" are Markov chains with an evolution that takes into account the state of other Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] This corresponds to the situation when the state space has a (Cartesian-) product form.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] See interacting particle system and stochastic cellular automata (probabilistic cellular automata).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] See for instance *Interaction of Markov Processes* or.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Many results for discrete-time Markov chains with finite state space can be generalized to chains with uncountable state space through Harris chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The use of Markov chains in Markov chain Monte Carlo methods covers cases where the process follows a continuous state space.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The definition of Markov processes in continuous time with general state space is more technical than the above.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov process $X=(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is a stochastic process adapted to a filtration $\mathbb {F} =({\mathcal {F}}_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ with values in a locally compact Polish space $(S,{\mathcal {B}}(S))$ (e.g., $(\mathbb {R} ,{\mathcal {B}}(\mathbb {R} ))$ ).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The latter essentially ensures that the conditional expectations of $X_{t}$ are regular, which, in simple terms, means that they behave "nicely".
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The function $(t,x,A)\mapsto P_{t}(x,A)$ is the so-called *transition function* of X and $(P_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ the *transition semigroup* of the process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Transition functions are generalizations of the transition matrices used in the setting with finite state space.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] where $\delta _{x}$ is the Dirac-measure in x , and $X:\Omega \times [0,\infty )\to S$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Or, if no probability measure P has been specified, the above equation defines a measure $P^{x}:=P(\cdot \mid X_{0}=x)$ on $\sigma (X_{s}:s\geq 0)$ under which the process X started in x is a Markov process by construction.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In other words, Markov processes can be defined either as stochastic processes X on a filtered probability space, or indirectly in terms of a transition semigroup (i.e., the transition probabilities of the process), which induces a probability space under which X has the Markov property.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Two states are said to *communicate* with each other if both are reachable from one another by a sequence of transitions that have positive probability.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] This is an equivalence relation which yields a set of communicating classes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A class is *closed* if the probability of leaving the class is zero.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is *irreducible* if there is one communicating class, the state space.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* has period *k* if *k* is the greatest common divisor of the number of transitions by which *i* can be reached, starting from *i*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The state is *periodic* if $k>1$ ; otherwise $k=1$ and the state is *aperiodic*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *transient* if, starting from *i*, there is a non-zero probability that the chain will never return to *i*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] It is called *recurrent* (or *persistent*) otherwise.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] State *i* is *positive recurrent* if $M_{i}$ is finite and *null recurrent* otherwise.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Periodicity, transience, recurrence and positive and null recurrence are class properties — that is, if one state has the property then all states in its communicating class have the property.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is called *absorbing* if there are no outgoing transitions from the state.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Since periodicity is a class property, if a Markov chain is irreducible, then all its states have the same period.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In particular, if one state is aperiodic, then the whole Markov chain is aperiodic.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If a finite Markov chain is irreducible, then all states are positive recurrent, and it has a unique stationary distribution given by $\pi _{i}=1/E[T_{i}]$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *ergodic* if it is aperiodic and positive recurrent.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In other words, a state *i* is ergodic if it is recurrent, has a period of 1, and has finite mean recurrence time.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If all states in an irreducible Markov chain are ergodic, then the chain is said to be ergodic.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Equivalently, there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] It can be shown that a finite state irreducible Markov chain is ergodic if it has an aperiodic state.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain with more than one state and just one out-going transition per state is either not irreducible or not aperiodic, hence cannot be ergodic.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call any irreducible, positive recurrent Markov chains ergodic, even periodic ones.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In fact, merely irreducible Markov chains correspond to ergodic processes, defined according to ergodic theory.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call a matrix *primitive* if there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The *index of primitivity*, or *exponent*, of a regular matrix, is the smallest k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The exponent is purely a graph-theoretic property, since it depends only on whether each entry of M is zero or positive, and therefore can be found on a directed graph with $\mathrm {sign} (M)$ as its adjacency matrix.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] There are several combinatorial results about the exponent when there are finitely many states.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If a Markov chain has a stationary distribution, then it can be converted to a measure-preserving dynamical system: Let the probability space be $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {N} }$ , where $\Sigma$ is the set of all states for the Markov chain.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Let the sigma-algebra on the probability space be generated by the cylinder sets.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Let the probability measure be generated by the stationary distribution, and the Markov chain transition.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Similarly we can construct such a dynamical system with $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {Z} }$ instead.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Since *irreducible* Markov chains with finite state spaces have a unique stationary distribution, the above construction is unambiguous for irreducible Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In ergodic theory, a measure-preserving dynamical system is called *ergodic* if any measurable subset S such that $T^{-1}(S)=S$ implies $S=\emptyset$ or $\Omega$ (up to a null set).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Given a Markov chain with a stationary distribution that is strictly positive on all states, the Markov chain is *irreducible* if its corresponding measure-preserving dynamical system is *ergodic*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] In some cases, apparently non-Markovian processes may still have Markovian representations, constructed by expanding the concept of the "current" and "future" states.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] For example, let *X* be a non-Markovian process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Then define a process *Y*, such that each state of *Y* represents a time-interval of states of *X*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If *Y* has the Markov property, then it is a Markovian representation of *X*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] An example of a non-Markovian process with a Markovian representation is an autoregressive time series of order greater than one.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The *hitting time* is the time, starting in a given set of states, until the chain arrives in a given state or set of states.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The distribution of such a time period has a phase type distribution.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The simplest such distribution is that of a single exponentially distributed transition.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] For a general Markov process X in continuous time (a CTMC or a process with general state space), the reverse process ${\overleftarrow {X}}=(X_{T-t})_{t\in [0,T]}$ from a fixed time $T>0$ is again a Markov process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] This follows directly from the Markov property: Informally speaking, the future and the past are independent given the present.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Under time-reversal, their roles are just interchanged.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] However, the reverse process is not time-homogeneous in general.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] If X is a CTMC, then by Kelly's lemma ${\overleftarrow {X}}$ has the same stationary distribution as the forward process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A chain is said to be *reversible* if the reversed process is the same as the forward process (in distribution).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov's criterion states that the necessary and sufficient condition for a Markov chain to be reversible is that the product of transition rates around a closed loop must be the same in both directions.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] One method of finding the stationary probability distribution, π, of an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain, *Q*, is by first finding its **embedded Markov chain (EMC)**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Strictly speaking, the EMC is a regular discrete-time Markov chain, sometimes referred to as a **jump process**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Each element of the one-step transition probability matrix of the EMC, *S*, is denoted by *s**ij*, and represents the conditional probability of transitioning from state *i* into state *j*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] where *I* is the identity matrix and diag(*Q*) is the diagonal matrix formed by selecting the main diagonal from the matrix *Q* and setting all other elements to zero.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] with $\varphi$ being a row vector, such that all elements in $\varphi$ are greater than 0 and $\|\varphi \|_{1}$ = 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] (*S* may be periodic, even if *Q* is not.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Another discrete-time process that may be derived from a continuous-time Markov chain is a δ-skeleton—the (discrete-time) Markov chain formed by observing *X*(*t*) at intervals of δ units of time.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The random variables *X*(0), *X*(δ), *X*(2δ), ... give the sequence of states visited by the δ-skeleton.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Markov models are used to model changing systems.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme is a special case of a Markov chain where the transition probability matrix has identical rows, which means that the next state is independent of even the current state (in addition to being independent of the past states).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme with only two possible states is known as a Bernoulli process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Note, however, by the Ornstein isomorphism theorem, that every aperiodic and irreducible Markov chain is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; thus, one might equally claim that Markov chains are a "special case" of Bernoulli schemes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism generally requires a complicated recoding.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism theorem is even a bit stronger: it states that *any* stationary stochastic process is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; the Markov chain is just one such example.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] When the Markov matrix is replaced by the adjacency matrix of a finite graph, the resulting shift is termed a **topological Markov chain** or a **subshift of finite type**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] A Markov matrix that is compatible with the adjacency matrix can then provide a measure on the subshift.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p01] Many chaotic dynamical systems are isomorphic to topological Markov chains; examples include diffeomorphisms of closed manifolds, the Prouhet–Thue–Morse system, the Chacon system, sofic systems, context-free systems and block-coding systems.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains have been employed in a wide range of topics across the natural and social sciences, and in technological applications.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] For example, a thermodynamic state operates under a probability distribution that is difficult or expensive to acquire.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Therefore, Markov Chain Monte Carlo method can be used to draw samples randomly from a black-box to approximate the probability distribution of attributes over a range of objects.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in lattice QCD simulations.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The enzyme (E) binds a substrate (S) and produces a product (P).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Each reaction is a state transition in a Markov chain.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] A reaction network is a chemical system involving multiple reactions and chemical species.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The simplest stochastic models of such networks treat the system as a continuous time Markov chain with the state being the number of molecules of each species and with reactions modeled as possible transitions of the chain.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains and continuous-time Markov processes are useful in chemistry when physical systems closely approximate the Markov property.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] For example, imagine a large number *n* of molecules in solution in state A, each of which can undergo a chemical reaction to state B with a certain average rate.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Perhaps the molecule is an enzyme, and the states refer to how it is folded.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The state of any single enzyme follows a Markov chain, and since the molecules are essentially independent of each other, the number of molecules in state A or B at a time is *n* times the probability a given molecule is in that state.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The classical model of enzyme activity, Michaelis–Menten kinetics, can be viewed as a Markov chain, where at each time step the reaction proceeds in some direction.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] While Michaelis-Menten is fairly straightforward, far more complicated reaction networks can also be modeled with Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm based on a Markov chain was also used to focus the fragment-based growth of chemicals in silico towards a desired class of compounds such as drugs or natural products.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] As a molecule is grown, a fragment is selected from the nascent molecule as the "current" state.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] It is not aware of its past (that is, it is not aware of what is already bonded to it).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] It then transitions to the next state when a fragment is attached to it.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The transition probabilities are trained on databases of authentic classes of compounds.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Also, the growth (and composition) of copolymers may be modeled using Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Based on the reactivity ratios of the monomers that make up the growing polymer chain, the chain's composition may be calculated (for example, whether monomers tend to add in alternating fashion or in long runs of the same monomer).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Due to steric effects, second-order Markov effects may also play a role in the growth of some polymer chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Similarly, it has been suggested that the crystallization and growth of some epitaxial superlattice oxide materials can be accurately described by Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in various areas of biology.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used throughout information processing.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Such idealized models can capture many of the statistical regularities of systems.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Even without describing the full structure of the system perfectly, such signal models can make possible very effective data compression through entropy encoding techniques such as arithmetic coding.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] They also allow effective state estimation and pattern recognition.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains also play an important role in reinforcement learning.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also the basis for hidden Markov models, which are an important tool in such diverse fields as telephone networks (which use the Viterbi algorithm for error correction), speech recognition and bioinformatics (such as in rearrangements detection).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The LZMA lossless data compression algorithm combines Markov chains with Lempel-Ziv compression to achieve very high compression ratios.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are the basis for the analytical treatment of queues (queueing theory).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Agner Krarup Erlang initiated the subject in 1917.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] This makes them critical for optimizing the performance of telecommunications networks, where messages must often compete for limited resources (such as bandwidth).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Numerous queueing models use continuous-time Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The PageRank of a webpage as used by Google is defined by a Markov chain.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] It is the probability to be at page i in the stationary distribution on the following Markov chain on all (known) webpages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] If N is the number of known webpages, and a page i has $k_{i}$ outgoing links from it then it has transition probability ${\frac {\alpha }{k_{i}}}+{\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are linked to and ${\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are not linked to.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The parameter $\alpha$ is taken to be about 0.85.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov models have also been used to analyze web navigation behavior of users.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] A user's web link transition on a particular website can be modeled using first- or second-order Markov models and can be used to make predictions regarding future navigation and to personalize the web page for an individual user.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain methods have also become very important for generating sequences of random numbers to accurately reflect very complicated desired probability distributions, via a process called Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] In recent years this has revolutionized the practicability of Bayesian inference methods, allowing a wide range of posterior distributions to be simulated and their parameters found numerically.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in finance and economics to model a variety of different phenomena, including the distribution of income, the size distribution of firms, asset prices and market crashes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Champernowne built a Markov chain model of the distribution of income in 1953.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Simon and co-author Charles Bonini used a Markov chain model to derive a stationary Yule distribution of firm sizes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Louis Bachelier was the first to observe that stock prices followed a random walk.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The random walk was later seen as evidence in favor of the efficient-market hypothesis and random walk models were popular in the literature of the 1960s.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Regime-switching models of business cycles were popularized by James D.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Hamilton (1989), who used a Markov chain to model switches between periods of high and low GDP growth (or, alternatively, economic expansions and recessions).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] A more recent example is the Markov switching multifractal model of Laurent E.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Fisher, which builds upon the convenience of earlier regime-switching models.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] It uses an arbitrarily large Markov chain to drive the level of volatility of asset returns.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Dynamic macroeconomics makes heavy use of Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] An example is using Markov chains to exogenously model prices of equity (stock) in a general equilibrium setting.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Credit rating agencies produce annual tables of the transition probabilities for bonds of different credit ratings.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are generally used in describing path-dependent arguments, where current structural configurations condition future outcomes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] An example is the reformulation of the idea, originally due to Karl Marx's *Das Kapital*, tying economic development to the rise of capitalism.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are employed in algorithmic music composition, particularly in software such as Csound, Max, and SuperCollider.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] In a first-order chain, the states of the system become note or pitch values, and a probability vector for each note is constructed, completing a transition probability matrix (see below).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm is constructed to produce output note values based on the transition matrix weightings, which could be MIDI note values, frequency (Hz), or any other desirable metric.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] A second-order Markov chain can be introduced by considering the current state *and* also the previous state, as indicated in the second table.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Higher, *n*th-order chains tend to "group" particular notes together, while 'breaking off' into other patterns and sequences occasionally.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] These higher-order chains tend to generate results with a sense of phrasal structure, rather than the 'aimless wandering' produced by a first-order system.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used structurally, as in Xenakis's Analogique A and B.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also used in systems which use a Markov model to react interactively to music input.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Usually musical systems need to enforce specific control constraints on the finite-length sequences they generate, but control constraints are not compatible with Markov models, since they induce long-range dependencies that violate the Markov hypothesis of limited memory.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] In order to overcome this limitation, a new approach has been proposed.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used to model many games of chance.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] The children's games Snakes and Ladders and "Hi Ho!
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Cherry-O", for example, are represented exactly by Markov chains.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] At each turn, the player starts in a given state (on a given square) and from there has fixed odds of moving to certain other states (squares).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain models have been used in advanced baseball analysis since 1960, although their use is still rare.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Each half-inning of a baseball game fits the Markov chain state when the number of runners and outs are considered.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] During any at-bat, there are 24 possible combinations of number of outs and position of the runners.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Mark Pankin shows that Markov chain models can be used to evaluate runs created for both individual players as well as a team.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] He also discusses various kinds of strategies and play conditions: how Markov chain models have been used to analyze statistics for game situations such as bunting and base stealing and differences when playing on grass vs.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes can also be used to generate superficially real-looking text given a sample document.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes are used in a variety of recreational "parody generator" software (see dissociated press, Jeff Harrison, Mark V.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/markov-chain-p02] Several open-source text generation libraries using Markov chains exist.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Currently, PageRank is not the only algorithm used by Google to order search results, but it is the first algorithm that was used by the company, and it is the best known.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] As of September 24, 2019, all patents associated with PageRank have expired.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank is a link analysis algorithm and it assigns a numerical weighting to each element of a hyperlinked set of documents, such as the World Wide Web, with the purpose of "measuring" its relative importance within the set.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The algorithm may be applied to any collection of entities with reciprocal quotations and references.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A PageRank results from a mathematical algorithm based on the Webgraph, created by all World Wide Web pages as nodes and hyperlinks as edges, taking into consideration authority hubs such as cnn.com or mayoclinic.org.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The rank value indicates an importance of a particular page.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A hyperlink to a page counts as a vote of support.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank of a page is defined recursively and depends on the number and PageRank metric of all pages that link to it ("incoming links").
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A page that is linked to by many pages with high PageRank receives a high rank itself.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Numerous academic papers concerning PageRank have been published since Page and Brin's original paper.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In practice, the PageRank concept may be vulnerable to manipulation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Research has been conducted into identifying falsely influenced PageRank rankings.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The goal is to find an effective means of ignoring links from documents with falsely influenced PageRank.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Other important content ranking systems from this era include the HITS algorithm invented by Jon Kleinberg (used by Teoma and now Ask.com), the IBM CLEVER project, the TrustRank algorithm, "dwell time" systems invented by Karl T.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Muth, the Hummingbird algorithm, and the SALSA algorithm.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The eigenvalue problem behind PageRank's algorithm was independently rediscovered and reused in many scoring problems.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In 1895, Edmund Landau suggested using it for determining the winner of a chess tournament.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A search engine called "RankDex" from IDD Information Services, designed by Robin Li in 1996, developed a strategy for site-scoring and page-ranking.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Li referred to his search mechanism as "link analysis," which involved ranking the popularity of a web site based on how many other sites had linked to it.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] RankDex, the first search engine with page-ranking and site-scoring algorithms, was launched in 1996.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Li filed a patent for the technology in RankDex in 1997; it was granted in 1999.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] He later used it when he founded Baidu in China in 2000.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google founder Larry Page referenced Li's work as a citation in some of his U.S. patents for PageRank.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Larry Page and Sergey Brin developed PageRank at Stanford University in 1996 as part of a research project to consider a new kind of search engine differentiated from then-dominant players like DEC's AltaVista.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] An interview with Héctor García-Molina, Stanford Computer Science professor and advisor to Sergey, provides background into the development of the page-rank algorithm.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Sergey Brin had the idea that information on the web could be ordered in a hierarchy by "link popularity": a page ranks higher as there are more links to it.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The system was developed with the help of Scott Hassan and Alan Steremberg, both of whom were cited by Page and Brin as being critical to the development of Google.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Rajeev Motwani and Terry Winograd co-authored with Page and Brin the first paper about the project, describing PageRank and the initial prototype of the Google search engine, published in 1998.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Shortly after, Page and Brin founded Google Inc., the company behind the Google search engine.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] While just one of many factors that determine the ranking of Google search results, PageRank continues to provide the basis for all of Google's web-search tools.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The name "PageRank" plays on the name of developer Larry Page, as well as of the concept of a web page.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The word is a trademark of Google, and the PageRank process was patented, with the patent granted in 2001, and now expired.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] However, the patent is assigned to Stanford University and not to Google.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google has exclusive license rights on the patent from Stanford University.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The university received 1.8 million shares of Google in exchange for use of the patent; it sold the shares in 2005 for $336 million.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank was influenced by citation analysis, early developed by Eugene Garfield in the 1950s at the University of Pennsylvania, and by Hyper Search, developed by Massimo Marchiori at the University of Padua.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In the same year PageRank was introduced (1998), Jon Kleinberg published his work on HITS.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google's founders cite Garfield, Marchiori, and Kleinberg in their original papers.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank algorithm outputs a probability distribution used to represent the likelihood that a person randomly clicking on links will arrive at any particular page.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank can be calculated for collections of documents of any size.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] It is assumed in several research papers that the distribution is evenly divided among all documents in the collection at the beginning of the computational process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank computations require several passes, called "iterations", through the collection to adjust approximate PageRank values to more closely reflect the theoretical true value.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A probability is expressed as a numeric value between 0 and 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A 0.5 probability is commonly expressed as a "50% chance" of something happening.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Hence, a document with a PageRank of 0.5 means there is a 50% chance that a person clicking on a random link will be directed to said document.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank works on the assumption that a page is important if many other important pages link to it.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] This means the more quality backlinks a page has, the higher its PageRank score.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Links from a page to itself are ignored.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Multiple outbound links from one page to another page are treated as a single link.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank is initialized to the same value for all pages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In the original form of PageRank, the sum of PageRank over all pages was the total number of pages on the web at that time, so each page in this example would have an initial value of 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] However, later versions of PageRank, and the remainder of this section, assume a probability distribution between 0 and 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Hence the initial value for each page in this example is 0.25.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank transferred from a given page to the targets of its outbound links upon the next iteration is divided equally among all outbound links.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] If the only links in the system were from pages **B**, **C**, and **D** to **A**, each link would transfer 0.25 PageRank to **A** upon the next iteration, for a total of 0.75.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Suppose instead that page **B** had a link to pages **C** and **A**, page **C** had a link to page **A**, and page **D** had links to all three pages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Thus, upon the first iteration, page **B** would transfer half of its existing value (0.125) to page **A** and the other half (0.125) to page **C**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Page **C** would transfer all of its existing value (0.25) to the only page it links to, **A**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Since **D** had three outbound links, it would transfer one third of its existing value, or approximately 0.083, to **A**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] At the completion of this iteration, page **A** will have a PageRank of approximately 0.458.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In other words, the PageRank conferred by an outbound link is equal to the document's own PageRank score divided by the number of outbound links **L( )**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] i.e. the PageRank value for a page **u** is dependent on the PageRank values for each page **v** contained in the set **Bu** (the set containing all pages linking to page **u**), divided by the number *L*(*v*) of links from page **v**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank theory holds that an imaginary surfer who is randomly clicking on links will eventually stop clicking.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The probability, at any step, that the person will continue following links is a damping factor *d*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The probability that they instead jump to any random page is *1 - d*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Various studies have tested different damping factors, but it is generally assumed that the damping factor will be set around 0.85.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] So any page's PageRank is derived in large part from the PageRanks of other pages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The damping factor adjusts the derived value downward.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The difference between them is that the PageRank values in the first formula sum to one, while in the second formula each PageRank is multiplied by *N* and the sum becomes *N*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A statement in Page and Brin's paper that "the sum of all PageRanks is one" and claims by other Google employees support the first variant of the formula above.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Page and Brin confused the two formulas in their most popular paper "The Anatomy of a Large-Scale Hypertextual Web Search Engine", where they mistakenly claimed that the latter formula formed a probability distribution over web pages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google recalculates PageRank scores each time it crawls the Web and rebuilds its index.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] As Google increases the number of documents in its collection, the initial approximation of PageRank decreases for all documents.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The formula uses a model of a *random surfer* who reaches their target site after several clicks, then switches to a random page.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank value of a page reflects the chance that the random surfer will land on that page by clicking on a link.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] It can be understood as a Markov chain in which the states are pages, and the transitions are the links between pages – all of which are all equally probable.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] If a page has no links to other pages, it becomes a sink and therefore terminates the random surfing process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] If the random surfer arrives at a sink page, it picks another URL at random and continues surfing again.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] When calculating PageRank, pages with no outbound links are assumed to link out to all other pages in the collection.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Their PageRank scores are therefore divided evenly among all other pages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In other words, to be fair with pages that are not sinks, these random transitions are added to all nodes in the Web.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] This residual probability, *d*, is usually set to 0.85, estimated from the frequency that an average surfer uses his or her browser's bookmark feature.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] where $p_{1},p_{2},...,p_{N}$ are the pages under consideration, $M(p_{i})$ is the set of pages that link to $p_{i}$ , $L(p_{j})$ is the number of outbound links on page $p_{j}$ , and N is the total number of pages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank values are the entries of the dominant right eigenvector of the modified adjacency matrix rescaled so that each column adds up to one.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] where the adjacency function $\ell (p_{i},p_{j})$ is the ratio between number of links outbound from page j to page i to the total number of outbound links of page j.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] i.e. the elements of each column sum up to 1, so the matrix is a stochastic matrix (for more details see the computation section below).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Thus this is a variant of the eigenvector centrality measure used commonly in network analysis.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Because of the large eigengap of the modified adjacency matrix above, the values of the PageRank eigenvector can be approximated to within a high degree of accuracy within only a few iterations.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google's founders, in their original paper, reported that the PageRank algorithm for a network consisting of 322 million links (in-edges and out-edges) converges to within a tolerable limit in 52 iterations.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The convergence in a network of half the above size took approximately 45 iterations.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Through this data, they concluded the algorithm can be scaled very well and that the scaling factor for extremely large networks would be roughly linear in $\log n$ , where n is the size of the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] As a result of Markov theory, it can be shown that the PageRank of a page is the probability of arriving at that page after a large number of clicks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] This happens to equal $t^{-1}$ where t is the expectation of the number of clicks (or random jumps) required to get from the page back to itself.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] One main disadvantage of PageRank is that it favors older pages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A new page, even a very good one, will not have many links unless it is part of an existing site (a site being a densely connected set of pages, such as Wikipedia).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Several strategies have been proposed to accelerate the computation of PageRank.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Various strategies to manipulate PageRank have been employed in concerted efforts to improve search results rankings and monetize advertising links.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] These strategies have severely impacted the reliability of the PageRank concept, which purports to determine which documents are actually highly valued by the Web community.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Since December 2007, when it started *actively* penalizing sites selling paid text links, Google has combatted link farms and other schemes designed to artificially inflate PageRank.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] How Google identifies link farms and other PageRank manipulation tools is among Google's trade secrets.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank can be computed either iteratively or algebraically.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The iterative method can be viewed as the power iteration method or the power method.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The basic mathematical operations performed are identical.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] where N is the total number of pages, and $p_{i};0$ is page i at time 0.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] where $\mathbf {R} _{i}(t)=PR(p_{i};t)$ and $\mathbf {1}$ is the column vector of length N containing only ones.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] where A denotes the adjacency matrix of the graph and K is the diagonal matrix with the outdegrees in the diagonal.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The probability calculation is made for each page at a time point, then repeated for the next time point.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Hence PageRank $\mathbf {R}$ is the principal eigenvector of ${\widehat {\mathcal {M}}}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Finally, if ${\mathcal {M}}$ has columns with only zero values, they should be replaced with the initial probability vector $\mathbf {P}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] that is, the PageRank of an undirected graph equals to the degree distribution vector if and only if the graph is regular, i.e., every vertex has the same degree.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A generalization of PageRank for the case of ranking two interacting groups of objects was described by Daugulis.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In applications it may be necessary to model systems having objects of two kinds where a weighted relation is defined on object pairs.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] This leads to considering bipartite graphs.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] For such graphs two related positive or nonnegative irreducible matrices corresponding to vertex partition sets can be defined.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] One can compute rankings of objects in both groups as eigenvectors corresponding to the maximal positive eigenvalues of these matrices.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Normed eigenvectors exist and are unique by the Perron or Perron–Frobenius theorem.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The relation weight is the product consumption rate.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Sarma et al. describe two random walk-based distributed algorithms for computing PageRank of nodes in a network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] One algorithm takes $O(\log n/\epsilon )$ rounds with high probability on any graph (directed or undirected), where n is the network size and $\epsilon$ is the reset probability ( $1-\epsilon$ , which is called the damping factor) used in the PageRank computation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] They also present a faster algorithm that takes $O({\sqrt {\log n}}/\epsilon )$ rounds in undirected graphs.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In both algorithms, each node processes and sends a number of bits per round that are polylogarithmic in n, the network size.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The Google Toolbar long had a PageRank feature which displayed a visited page's PageRank as a whole number between 0 (least popular) and 10 (most popular).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google had not disclosed the specific method for determining a Toolbar PageRank value, which was to be considered only a rough indication of the value of a website.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The "Toolbar Pagerank" was available for verified site maintainers through the Google Webmaster Tools interface.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] However, on October 15, 2009, a Google employee confirmed that the company had removed PageRank from its *Webmaster Tools* section, saying that "We've been telling people for a long time that they shouldn't focus on PageRank so much.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The "Toolbar Pagerank" was updated very infrequently.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In October 2014 Matt Cutts announced that another visible pagerank update would not be coming.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In March 2016 Google announced it would no longer support this feature, and the underlying API would soon cease to operate.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] On April 15, 2016, Google turned off display of PageRank Data in Google Toolbar, though the PageRank continued to be used internally to rank content in search results.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The search engine results page (SERP) is the actual result returned by a search engine in response to a keyword query.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The SERP consists of a list of links to web pages with associated text snippets, paid ads, featured snippets, and Q&A.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The SERP rank of a web page refers to the placement of the corresponding link on the SERP, where higher placement means higher SERP rank.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The SERP rank of a web page is a function not only of its PageRank, but of a relatively large and continuously adjusted set of factors (over 200).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Search engine optimization (SEO) is aimed at influencing the SERP rank for a website or a set of web pages.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Positioning of a webpage on Google SERPs for a keyword depends on relevance and reputation, also known as authority and popularity.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank is Google's indication of its assessment of the reputation of a webpage: It is non-keyword specific.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google uses a combination of webpage and website authority to determine the overall authority of a webpage competing for a keyword.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank of the HomePage of a website is the best indication Google offers for website authority.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] After the introduction of Google Places into the mainstream organic SERP, numerous other factors in addition to PageRank affect ranking a business in Local Business Results.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] When Google elaborated on the reasons for PageRank deprecation at Q&A #March 2016, they announced Links and Content as the Top Ranking Factors.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] RankBrain had earlier in October 2015 been announced as the #3 Ranking Factor, so the Top 3 Factors have been confirmed officially by Google.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The Google Directory PageRank was an 8-unit measurement.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Unlike the Google Toolbar, which showed a numeric PageRank value upon mouseover of the green bar, the Google Directory only displayed the bar, never the numeric values.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google Directory was closed on July 20, 2011.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] It was known that the PageRank shown in the Toolbar could easily be spoofed.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Redirection from one page to another, either via a HTTP 302 response or a "Refresh" meta tag, caused the source page to acquire the PageRank of the destination page.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Hence, a new page with PR 0 and no incoming links could have acquired PR 10 by redirecting to the Google home page.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Spoofing can usually be detected by performing a Google search for a source URL; if the URL of an entirely different site is displayed in the results, the latter URL may represent the destination of a redirection.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] For search engine optimization purposes, some companies offer to sell high PageRank links to webmasters.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] As links from higher-PR pages are believed to be more valuable, they tend to be more expensive.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] It can be an effective and viable marketing strategy to buy link advertisements on content pages of quality and relevant sites to drive traffic and increase a webmaster's link popularity.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] However, Google has publicly warned webmasters that if they are or were discovered to be selling links for the purpose of conferring PageRank and reputation, their links will be devalued (ignored in the calculation of other pages' PageRanks).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The practice of buying and selling is intensely debated across the Webmaster community.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Google advised webmasters to use the nofollow HTML attribute value on paid links.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] According to Matt Cutts, Google is concerned about webmasters who try to game the system, and thereby reduce the quality and relevance of Google search results.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In 2019, Google announced two additional link attributes providing hints about which links to consider or exclude within Search: `rel="ugc"` as a tag for user-generated content, such as comments; and `rel="sponsored"` as a tag for advertisements or other types of sponsored content.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Multiple `rel` values are also allowed, for example, `rel="ugc sponsored"` can be used to hint that the link came from user-generated content and is sponsored.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Even though PageRank has become less important for SEO purposes, the existence of back-links from more popular websites continues to push a webpage higher up in search rankings.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A more intelligent surfer that probabilistically hops from page to page depending on the content of the pages and query terms the surfer is looking for.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] This model is based on a query-dependent PageRank score of a page which as the name suggests is also a function of query.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] When given a multiple-term query, $Q=\{q1,q2,\cdots \}$ , the surfer selects a q according to some probability distribution, $P(q)$ , and uses that term to guide its behavior for a large number of steps.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] It then selects another term according to the distribution to determine its behavior, and so on.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The resulting distribution over visited web pages is QD-PageRank.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The mathematics of PageRank are entirely general and apply to any graph or network in any domain.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Thus, PageRank is now regularly used in bibliometrics, social and information network analysis, and for link prediction and recommendation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] It is used for systems analysis of road networks, and in biology, chemistry, neuroscience, and physics.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank has been used to quantify the scientific impact of researchers.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The underlying citation and collaboration networks are used in conjunction with PageRank algorithm in order to come up with a ranking system for individual publications which propagates to individual authors.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The new index known as pagerank-index (Pi) is demonstrated to be fairer compared to h-index in the context of many drawbacks exhibited by h-index.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] For the analysis of protein networks in biology PageRank is also a useful tool.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In any ecosystem, a modified version of PageRank may be used to determine species that are essential to the continuing health of the environment.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A similar newer use of PageRank is to rank academic doctoral programs based on their records of placing their graduates in faculty positions.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In PageRank terms, academic departments link to each other by hiring their faculty from each other (and from themselves).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A version of PageRank has recently been proposed as a replacement for the traditional Institute for Scientific Information (ISI) impact factor, and implemented at Eigenfactor as well as at SCImago.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Instead of merely counting total citations to a journal, the "importance" of each citation is determined in a PageRank fashion.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In neuroscience, the PageRank of a neuron in a neural network has been found to correlate with its relative firing rate.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Personalized PageRank is used by Twitter to present users with other accounts they may wish to follow.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] Swiftype's site search product builds a "PageRank that's specific to individual websites" by looking at each website's signals of importance and prioritizing content based on factors such as number of links from the home page.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] A Web crawler may use PageRank as one of a number of importance metrics it uses to determine which URL to visit during a crawl of the web.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] One of the early working papers that were used in the creation of Google is *Efficient crawling through URL ordering*, which discusses the use of a number of different importance metrics to determine how deeply, and how much of a site Google will crawl.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank is presented as one of a number of these importance metrics, though there are others listed such as the number of inbound and outbound links for a URL, and the distance from the root directory on a site to the URL.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The PageRank may also be used as a methodology to measure the apparent impact of a community like the Blogosphere on the overall Web itself.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] This approach uses therefore the PageRank to measure the distribution of attention in reflection of the Scale-free network paradigm.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In 2005, in a pilot study in Pakistan, *Structural Deep Democracy, SD2* was used for leadership selection in a sustainable agriculture group called Contact Youth.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] SD2 uses *PageRank* for the processing of the transitive proxy votes, with the additional constraints of mandating at least two initial proxies per voter, and all voters are proxy candidates.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] More complex variants can be built on top of SD2, such as adding specialist proxies and direct votes for specific issues, but SD2 as the underlying umbrella system, mandates that generalist proxies should always be used.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In sport the PageRank algorithm has been used to rank the performance of: teams in the National Football League (NFL) in the USA; individual soccer players; and athletes in the Diamond League.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank has been used to rank spaces or streets to predict how many people (pedestrians or vehicles) come to the individual spaces or streets.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] In lexical semantics it has been used to perform Word Sense Disambiguation, Semantic similarity, and also to automatically rank WordNet synsets according to how strongly they possess a given semantic property, such as positivity or negativity.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] How a traffic system changes its operational mode can be described by transitions between quasi-stationary states in correlation structures of traffic flow.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] PageRank has been used to identify and explore the dominant states among these quasi-stationary states in traffic systems.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] The nofollow relationship was added in an attempt to help combat spamdexing.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] As an example, people could previously create many message-board posts with links to their website to artificially inflate their PageRank.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] With the nofollow value, message-board administrators can modify their code to automatically insert "rel='nofollow'" to all hyperlinks in posts, thus preventing PageRank from being affected by those particular posts.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] This method of avoidance, however, also has various drawbacks, such as reducing the link value of legitimate comments.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/pagerank] This tactic had been used since the inception of the nofollow attribute, but may no longer be effective since Google announced that blocking PageRank transfer with nofollow does not redirect that PageRank to other links.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] The algorithm is also known as the **Von Mises iteration**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Power iteration is a very simple algorithm, but it may converge slowly.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] The most time-consuming operation of the algorithm is the multiplication of matrix A by a vector, so it is effective for a very large sparse matrix with appropriate implementation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] The speed of convergence is like $(\lambda _{2}/\lambda _{1})^{k}$ where k is the number of iterations, and $\lambda _{1}$ and $\lambda _{2}$ are, respectively, the eigenvalue of largest absolute value and an eigenvalue of second-largest absolute value (see a later section).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] In other words, convergence is exponential with base being the spectral gap.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] The power iteration algorithm starts with a vector $b_{0}$ , which may be an approximation to the dominant eigenvector or a random vector.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] So, at every iteration, the vector $b_{k}$ is multiplied by the matrix A and normalized.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] and the starting vector $b_{0}$ has a nonzero component in the direction of an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue, then a subsequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ converges to an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Without the two assumptions above, the sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ does not necessarily converge.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] where $v_{1}$ is an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue, and $\|r_{k}\|\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] The presence of the term $e^{i\phi _{k}}$ implies that $\left(b_{k}\right)$ does not converge unless $e^{i\phi _{k}}=1$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] converges to the dominant eigenvalue (with Rayleigh quotient).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] The vector $b_{k}$ converges to an associated eigenvector.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Ideally, one should use the Rayleigh quotient in order to get the associated eigenvalue.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] This algorithm is used to calculate the *Google PageRank*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Let A be decomposed into its Jordan canonical form: $A=VJV^{-1}$ , where the first column of V is an eigenvector of A corresponding to the dominant eigenvalue $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Since generically, the dominant eigenvalue of A is unique, the first Jordan block of J is the $1\times 1$ matrix $[\lambda _{1}],$ where $\lambda _{1}$ is the largest eigenvalue of A in magnitude.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] By assumption, $b_{0}$ has a nonzero component in the direction of the dominant eigenvector, so $c_{1}\neq 0$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] The sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ is bounded, so it contains a convergent subsequence.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Note that the eigenvector corresponding to the dominant eigenvalue is only unique up to a scalar, so although the sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ may not converge, $b_{k}$ is nearly an eigenvector of A for large k .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Suppose that $\lambda _{1}$ is the dominant eigenvalue, so that $|\lambda _{1}|>|\lambda _{j}|$ for all $j>1$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] If $b_{0}$ is chosen randomly (with uniform probability), then $c_{1}\neq 0$ with probability 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Therefore, $b_{k}$ converges to (a multiple of) the eigenvector $v_{1}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Thus, the method converges slowly if there is an eigenvalue close in magnitude to the dominant eigenvalue.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Although the power iteration method approximates only one eigenvalue of a matrix, it remains useful for certain computational problems.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] For instance, Google uses it to calculate the PageRank of documents in their search engine, and Twitter uses it to show users recommendations of whom to follow.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] The power iteration method is especially suitable for sparse matrices, such as the web matrix, or as the matrix-free method that does not require storing the coefficient matrix A explicitly, but can instead access a function evaluating matrix-vector products $Ax$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] For non-symmetric matrices that are well-conditioned the power iteration method can outperform more complex Arnoldi iteration.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] For symmetric matrices, the power iteration method is rarely used, since its convergence speed can be easily increased without sacrificing the small cost per iteration; see, e.g., Lanczos iteration and LOBPCG.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Some of the more advanced eigenvalue algorithms can be understood as variations of the power iteration.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] For instance, the inverse iteration method applies power iteration to the matrix $A^{-1}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Other algorithms look at the whole subspace generated by the vectors $b_{k}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] This subspace is known as the Krylov subspace.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] It can be computed by Arnoldi iteration or Lanczos iteration.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/power-iteration] Gram iteration is a super-linear and deterministic method to compute the largest eigenpair.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In mathematics, a **random walk** is a stochastic process that describes a path that consists of a succession of random steps on some mathematical space.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] An elementary example of a random walk is one on the integer number line $\mathbb {Z}$ which starts at 0, and at each step moves +1 or −1 with equal probability.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Other examples include the path traced by a molecule as it travels in a liquid or a gas (see Brownian motion), the search path of a foraging animal, or the price of a fluctuating stock and the financial status of a gambler.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Random walks have applications to engineering and many scientific fields including ecology, psychology, computer science, physics, chemistry, biology, economics, and sociology.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The term *random walk* was first introduced by Karl Pearson in 1905.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Realizations of random walks can be obtained by Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In certain contexts random walk is sometimes known as a **drunkard's walk**.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A popular random walk model is that of a random walk on a regular lattice, where at each step the location jumps to another site according to some probability distribution.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In a *simple random walk*, the location can only jump to neighboring sites of the lattice, forming a lattice path.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In a *simple symmetric random walk* on a locally finite lattice, the probabilities of the location jumping to each one of its immediate neighbors are the same.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The best-studied example is the random walk on the *d*-dimensional integer lattice (sometimes called the hypercubic lattice) $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] If, in addition, the state space is finite, the random walk model is called a *simple bordered symmetric random walk*, and the transition probabilities depend on the location of the state because on margin and corner states the movement is limited.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] An elementary example of a random walk is the random walk on the integer number line, $\mathbb {Z}$ , which starts at 0 and at each step moves +1 or −1 with equal probability.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This walk can be illustrated as follows.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A marker is placed at zero on the number line, and a fair coin is flipped.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] If it lands on heads, the marker is moved one unit to the right.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] If it lands on tails, the marker is moved one unit to the left.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] After five flips, the marker could now be on -5, -3, -1, 1, 3, 5.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] With five flips, three heads and two tails, in any order, it will land on 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] See the figure below for an illustration of the possible outcomes of 5 flips.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This series (the sum of the sequence of −1s and 1s) gives the net distance walked, if each part of the walk is of length one.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] That is, the mean of all coin flips approaches zero as the number of flips increases.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This hints that $E(|S_{n}|)\,\!$ , the expected translation distance after *n* steps, should be of the order of ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] To answer the question of how many times will a random walk cross a boundary line if permitted to continue walking forever, a simple random walk on $\mathbb {Z}$ will cross every point an infinite number of times.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This result has many names: the *level-crossing phenomenon*, *recurrence* or the *gambler's ruin*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The reason for the last name is as follows: a gambler with a finite amount of money will eventually lose when playing *a fair game* against a bank with an infinite amount of money.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The gambler's money will perform a random walk, and it will reach zero at some point, and the game will be over.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] If *a* and *b* are positive integers, then the expected number of steps until a one-dimensional simple random walk starting at 0 first hits *b* or −*a* is *ab*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The probability that this walk will hit *b* before −*a* is $a/(a+b)$ , which can be derived from the fact that simple random walk is a martingale.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] And these expectations and hitting probabilities can be computed in $O(a+b)$ in the general one-dimensional random walk Markov chain.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Some of the results mentioned above can be derived from properties of Pascal's triangle.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The number of different walks of *n* steps where each step is +1 or −1 is 2*n*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] For the simple random walk, each of these walks is equally likely.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In order for *Sn* to be equal to a number *k* it is necessary and sufficient that the number of +1 in the walk exceeds those of −1 by *k*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] It follows +1 must appear (*n* + *k*)/2 times among *n* steps of a walk, hence the number of walks which satisfy $S_{n}=k$ equals the number of ways of choosing (*n* + *k*)/2 elements from an *n* element set, denoted ${\textstyle n \choose (n+k)/2}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] For this to have meaning, it is necessary that *n* + *k* be an even number, which implies *n* and *k* are either both even or both odd.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Therefore, the probability that $S_{n}=k$ is equal to ${\textstyle 2^{-n}{n \choose (n+k)/2}}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] By representing entries of Pascal's triangle in terms of factorials and using Stirling's formula, one can obtain good estimates for these probabilities for large values of n .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This relation with Pascal's triangle is demonstrated for small values of *n*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] At zero turns, the only possibility will be to remain at zero.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] However, at one turn, there is one chance of landing on −1 or one chance of landing on 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] At two turns, a marker at 1 could move to 2 or back to zero.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A marker at −1, could move to −2 or back to zero.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Therefore, there is one chance of landing on −2, two chances of landing on zero, and one chance of landing on 2.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The central limit theorem and the law of the iterated logarithm describe important aspects of the behavior of simple random walks on $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In particular, the former entails that as *n* increases, the probabilities (proportional to the numbers in each row) approach a normal distribution.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] taking the limit (and observing that ${\textstyle {1}/{\sqrt {n}}}$ corresponds to the spacing of the scaling grid) one finds the gaussian density ${\textstyle f(x)={\frac {1}{2{\sqrt {\pi }}}}e^{-{x^{2}}}}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Indeed, for a absolutely continuous random variable ${\textstyle X}$ with density ${\textstyle f_{X}}$ it holds ${\textstyle \mathbb {P} \left(X\in [x,x+dx)\right)=f_{X}(x)dx}$ , with ${\textstyle dx}$ corresponding to an infinitesimal spacing.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] As a direct generalization, one can consider random walks on crystal lattices (infinite-fold abelian covering graphs over finite graphs).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Actually it is possible to establish the central limit theorem and large deviation theorem in this setting.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The heterogeneous random walk draws in each time step a random number that determines the local jumping probabilities and then a random number that determines the actual jump direction.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The main question is the probability of staying in each of the various sites after t jumps, and in the limit of this probability when t is very large.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In higher dimensions, the set of randomly walked points has interesting geometric properties.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In fact, one gets a discrete fractal, that is, a set which exhibits stochastic self-similarity on large scales.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] On small scales, one can observe "jaggedness" resulting from the grid on which the walk is performed.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The trajectory of a random walk is the collection of points visited, considered as a set with disregard to *when* the walk arrived at the point.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In one dimension, the trajectory is simply all points between the minimum height and the maximum height the walk achieved (both are, on average, on the order of ${\sqrt {n}}$ ).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] To visualize the two-dimensional case, one can imagine a person walking randomly around a city.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The city is effectively infinite and arranged in a square grid of sidewalks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] At every intersection, the person randomly chooses one of the four possible routes (including the one originally travelled from).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Formally, this is a random walk on the set of all points in the plane with integer coordinates.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] To answer the question of the person ever getting back to the original starting point of the walk, this is the 2-dimensional equivalent of the level-crossing problem discussed above.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In 1921 George Pólya proved that the person almost surely would in a 2-dimensional random walk, but for 3 dimensions or higher, the probability of returning to the origin decreases as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In 3 dimensions, the probability decreases to roughly 34%.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The mathematician Shizuo Kakutani was known to refer to this result with the following quote: "A drunk man will find his way home, but a drunk bird may get lost forever".
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Paul Erdős and Samuel James Taylor also showed in 1960 that for dimensions less or equal than 4, two independent random walks starting from any two given points have infinitely many intersections almost surely, but for dimensions higher than 5, they almost surely intersect only finitely often.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The asymptotic function for a two-dimensional random walk as the number of steps increases is given by a Rayleigh distribution.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The probability distribution is a function of the radius from the origin and the step length is constant for each step.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Here, the step length is assumed to be 1, N is the total number of steps and r is the radius from the origin.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A Wiener process is a stochastic process with similar behavior to Brownian motion, the physical phenomenon of a minute particle diffusing in a fluid.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A Wiener process is the scaling limit of random walk in dimension 1.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This means that if there is a random walk with very small steps, there is an approximation to a Wiener process (and, less accurately, to Brownian motion).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] To be more precise, if the step size is ε, one needs to take a walk of length *L*/ε2 to approximate a Wiener length of *L*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] As the step size tends to 0 (and the number of steps increases proportionally), random walk converges to a Wiener process in an appropriate sense.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Formally, if *B* is the space of all paths of length *L* with the maximum topology, and if *M* is the space of measure over *B* with the norm topology, then the convergence is in the space *M*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Similarly, a Wiener process in several dimensions is the scaling limit of random walk in the same number of dimensions.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A random walk is a discrete fractal (a function with integer dimensions; 1, 2, ...), but a Wiener process trajectory is a true fractal, and there is a connection between the two.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] For example, take a random walk until it hits a circle of radius *r* times the step length.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The average number of steps it performs is *r*2.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This fact is the *discrete version* of the fact that a Wiener process walk is a fractal of Hausdorff dimension 2.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In two dimensions, the average number of points the same random walk has on the *boundary* of its trajectory is *r*4/3.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This corresponds to the fact that the boundary of the trajectory of a Wiener process is a fractal of dimension 4/3, a fact predicted by Mandelbrot using simulations but proved only in 2000 by Lawler, Schramm and Werner.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A Wiener process enjoys many symmetries a random walk does not.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] For example, a Wiener process walk is invariant to rotations, but the random walk is not, since the underlying grid is not (random walk is invariant to rotations by 90 degrees, but Wiener processes are invariant to rotations by, for example, 17 degrees too).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This means that in many cases, problems on a random walk are easier to solve by translating them to a Wiener process, solving the problem there, and then translating back.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] On the other hand, some problems are easier to solve with random walks due to its discrete nature.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Random walk and Wiener process can be *coupled*, namely manifested on the same probability space in a dependent way that forces them to be quite close.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The simplest such coupling is the Skorokhod embedding, but there exist more precise couplings, such as Komlós–Major–Tusnády approximation theorem.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The convergence of a random walk toward the Wiener process is controlled by the central limit theorem, and by Donsker's theorem.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] where *t* is the time elapsed since the start of the random walk, $\varepsilon$ is the size of a step of the random walk, and $\delta t$ is the time elapsed between two successive steps.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This corresponds to the Green's function of the diffusion equation that controls the Wiener process, which suggests that, after a large number of steps, the random walk converges toward a Wiener process.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The two expressions of the variance above correspond to the distribution associated to the vector ${\vec {R}}$ that links the two ends of the random walk, in 3D.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The variance associated to each component $R_{x}$ , $R_{y}$ or $R_{z}$ is only one third of this value (still in 3D).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A random walk having a step size that varies according to a normal distribution ${\mathcal {N}}(\mu ,\sigma ^{2})$ , $\mu$ being the mean and $\sigma$ being the standard deviation, is used as a model for real-world time-series data such as financial markets.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Here, the step size is given by the inverse cumulative normal distribution $\Phi ^{-1}(x,\mu ,\sigma ),$ where $x\in \{0,1\}$ is a uniformly distributed random number.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] If $\mu$ is nonzero, the random walk will vary about a linear trend.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] If $v_{s}$ is the starting value of the random walk, the expected value after n steps will be $v_{s}+n\mu$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] But for the Gaussian random walk, this is just the standard deviation of the translation distance's distribution after n steps.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Hence, if $\mu =0$ , and since the root mean square (RMS) translation distance is one standard deviation, there is a 68.27% probability that the RMS translation distance after n steps will fall between $\pm \sigma {\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The number of distinct sites visited by a single random walker $S(t)$ has been studied extensively for square and cubic lattices and for fractals.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This quantity is useful for the analysis of problems of trapping and kinetic reactions.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] It is also related to the vibrational density of states, diffusion reactions processes and spread of populations in ecology.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Therefore, it is impossible to encode ${\{Z_{n}\}_{n=1}^{N}}$ using a binary code of less than $NR(D_{\theta })$ bits and recover it with expected mean squared error less than $D_{\theta }$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In financial economics, the random walk hypothesis is used to model share prices and other factors.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Empirical studies found some deviations from this theoretical model, especially in short term and long term correlations.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In semiconductor manufacturing, random walks are used to analyze the effects of thermal treatment at smaller nodes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] It is applied to understand the diffusion of dopants, defects and other impurities during the critical fabrication steps.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Random walk treatments are also used to study the diffusion of reactants, products and plasma during chemical vapor deposition processes.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Continuum diffusion has been used to study the flow of gases, at macroscopic scales, in CVD reactors.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] However, smaller dimensions and increased complexity has forced us to treat them with random walk.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This allows for accurate analysis of stochastic processes, at molecular level and smaller, in semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In computer science, random walks have been used to estimate the size of the Web.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In computer programming it is possible to calculate pi with a random walk.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Random walks have been used in network analysis to calculate the probability two unlinked nodes will be linked in the future based on the current state of the network.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Various algorithms are discussed in including PageRank and supervised random walks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In image segmentation, random walks are used to determine the labels (i.e., "object" or "background") to associate with each pixel.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This algorithm is typically referred to as the random walker segmentation algorithm.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The Twitter website used random walks to make suggestions of whom to follow.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] As mentioned, the range of natural phenomena which have been subject to attempts at description by some flavour of random walks is considerable.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This is particularly the case in the fields of physics, chemistry, materials science, and biology.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A number of types of stochastic processes have been considered that are similar to the pure random walks but where the simple structure is allowed to be more generalized.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The *pure* structure can be characterized by the steps being defined by independent and identically distributed random variables.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Random walks can take place on a variety of spaces, such as graphs, the integers, the real line, the plane or higher-dimensional vector spaces, on curved surfaces or higher-dimensional Riemannian manifolds, and on groups.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] It is also possible to define random walks which take their steps at random times, and in that case, the position X t has to be defined for all times *t* ∈ [0, +∞).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Specific cases or limits of random walks include the Lévy flight and diffusion models such as Brownian motion.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A random walk of length *k* on a possibly infinite graph *G* with a root *0* is a stochastic process with random variables $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{k}$ such that $X_{1}=0$ and ${X_{i+1}}$ is a vertex chosen uniformly at random from the neighbors of $X_{i}$ .
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Then the number $p_{v,w,k}(G)$ is the probability that a random walk of length *k* starting at *v* ends at *w*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In particular, if *G* is a graph with root *0*, $p_{0,0,2k}$ is the probability that a $2k$ -step random walk returns to *0*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Building on the analogy from the earlier section on higher dimensions, assume now that our city is no longer a perfect square grid.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] When our person reaches a certain junction, he picks between the variously available roads with equal probability.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Thus, if the junction has seven exits the person will go to each one with probability one-seventh.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] It turns out that under rather mild conditions, the answer is still yes, but depending on the graph, the answer to the variant question 'Will two persons meet again?' may not be that they meet infinitely often almost surely.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] An example of a case where the person will reach his home almost surely is when the lengths of all the blocks are between *a* and *b* (where *a* and *b* are any two finite positive numbers).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Notice that we do not assume that the graph is planar, i.e. the city may contain tunnels and bridges.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] One way to prove this result is using the connection to electrical networks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Take a map of the city and place a one ohm resistor on every block.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Now measure the "resistance between a point and infinity".
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In other words, choose some number *R* and take all the points in the electrical network with distance bigger than *R* from our point and wire them together.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This is now a finite electrical network, and we may measure the resistance from our point to the wired points.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The limit is called the *resistance between a point and infinity*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In other words, in a transient system, one only needs to overcome a finite resistance to get to infinity from any point.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In a recurrent system, the resistance from any point to infinity is infinite.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This characterization of transience and recurrence is very useful, and specifically it allows us to analyze the case of a city drawn in the plane with the distances bounded.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A random walk on a graph is a very special case of a Markov chain.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Unlike a general Markov chain, random walk on a graph enjoys a property called *time symmetry* or *reversibility*.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Roughly speaking, this property, also called the principle of detailed balance, means that the probabilities to traverse a given path in one direction or the other have a very simple connection between them (if the graph is regular, they are just equal).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This property has important consequences.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Starting in the 1980s, much research has gone into connecting properties of the graph to random walks.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In addition to the electrical network connection described above, there are important connections to isoperimetric inequalities, see more here, functional inequalities such as Sobolev and Poincaré inequalities and properties of solutions of Laplace's equation.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A significant portion of this research was focused on Cayley graphs of finitely generated groups.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In many cases these discrete results carry over to, or are derived from manifolds and Lie groups.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In the context of random graphs, particularly that of the Erdős–Rényi model, analytical results to some properties of random walkers have been obtained.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] A good reference for random walk on graphs is the online book by Aldous and Fill.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] If the transition kernel $p(x,y)$ is itself random (based on an environment $\omega$ ) then the random walk is called a "random walk in random environment".
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] When the law of the random walk includes the randomness of $\omega$ , the law is called the annealed law; on the other hand, if $\omega$ is seen as fixed, the law is called a quenched law.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] See the book of Hughes, the book of Revesz, or the lecture notes of Zeitouni.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] We can think about choosing every possible edge with the same probability as maximizing uncertainty (entropy) locally.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] We could also do it globally – in maximal entropy random walk (MERW) we want all paths to be equally probable, or in other words: for every two vertexes, each path of given length is equally probable.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This random walk has much stronger localization properties.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] There are a number of interesting models of random paths in which each step depends on the past in a complicated manner.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] All are more complex for solving analytically than the usual random walk; still, the behavior of any model of a random walker is obtainable using computers.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] The self-avoiding walk of length *n* on $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ is the random *n*-step path which starts at the origin, makes transitions only between adjacent sites in $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ , never revisit a site, and is chosen uniformly among all such paths.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] In two dimensions, due to self-trapping, a typical self-avoiding walk is very short, while in higher dimension it grows beyond all bounds.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] This model has often been used in polymer physics (since the 1960s).
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Random walk chosen to maximize entropy rate, has much stronger localization properties.
[src:pagerank-algorithm/random-walk] Random walks where the direction of movement at one time is correlated with the direction of movement at the next time.
